definition:
Let $(X,{\mathfrak{B}})$ be a measurable space. The measure $\mu$ on $X$
defined by $$\mu(A) = \left\{
\begin{array}{ll}
n & \text{if}\, A\, \text{ has exactly }\, n\, \text{ elements} \\
\infty & \text{otherwise.}
\end{array}
\right.$$ for all $A\in{\mathfrak{B}}$ is called the *counting measure*
on $X$. Usually this is applied when $X$ is countable, e.g.
${\mathbb{N}}$ or ${\mathbb{Z}}$.
